-- tAbout the Editor -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays and interviews provides a frank look at the nature and purposes of prisons in the United States from the perspective of the prisoners. Written by Native American, African American, Latino, Asian, and European American prisoners, the book examines captivity and democracy, the racial "other," gender and violence, and the stigma of a suspect humanity. Contributors include those incarcerated for social and political acts, such as conscientious objection, antiwar activism, black liberation, and gang activities. Among those interviewed are Philip Berrigan, Marilyn Buck, Angela Y. Davis, George Jackson, and Laura Whitehorn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPrisonerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPrisonerszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPrisoners' writings, American. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Angela Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Joy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079148310740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483107/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles